abstract = {We present an exhaustive census of Lyman alpha (Ly{\$}\backslashalpha{\$}) emission in the general galaxy population at {\$}3{\textless}z{\textless}4.6{\$}. We use the Michigan/Magellan Fiber System (M2FS) spectrograph to study a stellar mass (M{\$}{\_}*{\$}) selected sample of 625 galaxies homogeneously distributed in the range {\$}7.6{\textless}\backslashlog{\{}\backslashmbox{\{}M{\$}{\_}*{\$}/M{\$}{\_}{\{}$\backslash$odot{\}}{\$}{\}}{\}}{\textless}10.6{\$}. Our sample is selected from the 3D-HST/CANDELS survey, which provides the complementary data to estimate Ly{\$}\backslashalpha{\$} equivalent widths ({\$}W{\_}{\{}Ly\backslashalpha{\}}{\$}) and escape fractions ({\$}f{\_}{\{}esc{\}}{\$}) for our galaxies. We find both quantities to anti-correlate with M{\$}{\_}*{\$}, star-formation rate (SFR), UV luminosity, and UV slope ({\$}\backslashbeta{\$}). We then model the {\$}W{\_}{\{}Ly\backslashalpha{\}}{\$} distribution as a function of M{\$}{\_}{\{}UV{\}}{\$} and {\$}\backslashbeta{\$} using a Bayesian approach. Based on our model and matching the properties of typical Lyman break galaxy (LBG) selections, we conclude that the {\$}W{\_}{\{}Ly\backslashalpha{\}}{\$} distribution in such samples is heavily dependent on the limiting M{\$}{\_}{\{}UV{\}}{\$} of the survey. Regarding narrowband surveys, we find their {\$}W{\_}{\{}Ly\backslashalpha{\}}{\$} selections to bias samples toward low M{\$}{\_}*{\$}, while their line-flux limitations preferentially leave out low-SFR galaxies. We can also use our model to predict the fraction of Ly{\$}\backslashalpha{\$}-emitting LBGs at {\$}4\backslashleqslant z\backslashleqslant 7{\$}. We show that reported drops in the Ly{\$}\backslashalpha{\$} fraction at {\$}z\backslashgeqslant6{\$}, usually attributed to the rapidly increasing neutral gas fraction of the universe, can also be explained by survey M{\$}{\_}{\{}UV{\}}{\$} incompleteness. This result does not dismiss reionization occurring at {\$}z\backslashsim7{\$}, but highlights that current data is not inconsistent with this process taking place at {\$}z{\textgreater}7{\$}.},
